rComments: Professor Tran is super unapproachable and says mean things about students she doesn't like (not specifics but general). Even if its not you shes talking about it, it makes you feel uncomfortable as a student to hear. If she likes you, she'll help you. If not, ( which is arbitrarily determined), shes gonna be mean. Easy marker tho

She is an amazing prof. If you use your time wisely and go to her office hours to ask questions, you will enjoy the class a lot. Her way of teaching is so elegant, as if she is telling a story. Not to mention her intelligence, she never looks at her notes when she lectures and answers every question with sheer confidence.
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Gives good feedback', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: I feel threatened after her class. Good job.
Unclear, weak lectures. Emotional. I don't recommend her. Choose carefully if doing SEA.

Professor Tran is an excellent scholar and one of the few professors that teaches the necessary skills you require at an university. If you simply take interest in what she has to say and do the work she assigns, than you are guaranteed a good grade and even a friend at a very impersonal place called the University of Toronto.

Although I personally am not a fan of Professor Tran. A lot of students do seem to enjoy her class. Either you love her or hate her I think. I found her lectures very difficult to follow. As the course was a survey course (Yes I do acknowledge they are hard to teach) but I found hers downright confusing. I felt even my TA was confused at times.

Prof. Tran is a really good professor at U of T. Highly educated and knowledgeable, she is a no-nonsense person who does not suffer fools or students who do not work hard (as it should be). She is treats one like an adult, and expects students to read and think. She is accessible and available if you use your resources as you should at U of T.

Professor Tran is one of the few academics at the school that is dedicated to teaching her students. If you do the readings and go to class then you're fine but she expects her students to have thought about the material. She treats you like an adult and is a very fair marker. If you're not up for the challenge then don't take the course.

Unless you have a background in Southeast Asian History - do NOT take this class! Prof. Tran is one of the worst profs at UofT - hard to believe she is Ivy League educated. Lectures are completely incomprehensible and taking notes becomes a Herculean task. Ended up dropping this class, I just couldn't take it any longer!!

Ultimately, she is a good professor. It might seem like she is boring or scattered sometimes but in the end everything she says comes together. As for tutorials, yes they are worth 40% of the final but I got like 5/10 or less most weeks and still managed an A- in the course. Really just go to lecture, read and try hard on papers. Try harder people.

She taught Intro to Southeast Asia (200 level course). I hope people will take negative comments about her seriously because she is by far the most incompetent professor at the U of T. Her lectures are scattered; there is no sense of order. You are too afraid to state an opinion that would counter hers. Please stay away from her courses!

Bit confounded by the negative reviews. Took her course late in 3yr. Possibly the first course at UofT that challenged me to come to my own conclusions about readings, without being spoon-fed someone else's analysis first.If you are interested in the subject matter, take the course, do your readings, and be prepared to think a little.

Please read this before taking a course with Tran! I am not trying to be bias, but she lecture a 200 level course at a 400 level.  Many peers whom I've spoken to found her difficult to understand, she was very unclear in lectures. Each tutorial is worth 2%, worth a total of 40% = each week you better have your readings done or face getting zeros!
AVOID COURSES LECTURED BY HER>.. SHE IS BY FAR THE MOST HORRIBLE PROF!

overall a good course for someone with some Southeast Asia background/interest..  exam were straight foward as we was given exam questions prior to the exam for review..  no surprise on the exam nor quiz..

Methods of evaluation were misleading and unfair; did not reflect what was learned in lecture and readings. Questions on tests were very picky, small details. Stated that she would not assume that all students had a prior background in SE Asian history, but her lectures said otherwise. She also liked to talk about herself a bit too much.
